{% extends "base.html.jinja" %}
{% import "_macros.html.jinja" as m %}

{% block title %}Research - WC 2026 Prediction Desk{% endblock %}

{% block content %}

<h1 class="page">Research</h1>
<p class="lede">How the models earned their places. This page reconstructs the
evolution of the prediction stack from the evidence on disk, generation by
generation, including the ideas that were measured and rejected. Every number
can be regenerated with the commands at the end; the
<a href="../docs/whitepaper/README.md">whitepaper</a> remains the full scholarly
account and each section is linked where it applies.</p>

<div class="caveat"><b>Reading the evidence.</b> Two kinds of numbers appear
below and they must not be mixed. Held-out and walk-forward tables never let a
model see its test labels and are the trustworthy basis for decisions. The
realized backtest scores squads on rounds the WC-retrained GBM later trained
on, so gbm and ensemble rows there are upper bounds, useful for narrative and
unfair for comparison.</div>

{# ---------------- 1. Timeline ---------------- #}
<div class="srule"><span class="no">1</span><h2>Model generations</h2></div>
<ol class="timeline">
  {% for date, title, desc in timeline %}
  <li>
    <span class="d">{{ date }}</span>
    <span class="t"><b>{{ title }}</b><p>{{ desc }}</p></span>
  </li>
  {% endfor %}
</ol>

<div class="srule"><span class="no">1a</span><h2>Superseded generations</h2></div>
<div class="tbl-wrap">
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Generation</th><th>Status</th><th>Introduced</th><th>Why it was replaced</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for g in generations %}
    <tr>
      <td>{{ g.label }}</td>
      <td><span class="badge {{ g.status }}">{{ g.status }}</span></td>
      <td class="num">{{ g.introduced }}</td>
      <td class="wraps">{{ g.summary }}</td>
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>

{# ---------------- 2. Realized performance ---------------- #}
<div class="srule"><span class="no">2</span><h2>Realized performance</h2></div>
<div class="prose"><p>The cross-model backtest rebuilds every backend's squad
for each completed round and scores it with realized fantasy points, next to
the squad the user actually fielded and a 500-trial random baseline. The
spread is the headline. Every backend beats random by a wide margin, and the
per-position ensemble sits near the top while remaining honest about where its
components win.</p></div>

{{ m.figure(figs.get("fig_backtest_cumulative"), "1",
   "Cumulative realized squad points per backend across the completed rounds.
    The user's actual squad (dashed) and the random baseline (dotted) frame the
    field. The gbm and ensemble series carry the in-sample caveat stated above.") }}

{{ m.figure(figs.get("fig_backtest_rounds"), "2",
   "The same data per round. No backend wins every round, which is the
    empirical case for per-position routing over a single champion.") }}

{% if backtest %}
<div class="tbl-wrap">
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Source</th>{% for r in backtest.rounds %}<th class="n">{{ r.stage }}</th>{% endfor %}<th class="n">Total</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for key, series in backtest.series.items() %}
    <tr>
      <td class="role">{{ backend_labels.get(key, key) }}</td>
      {% for v in series %}<td class="n">{{ "%.0f"|format(v) }}</td>{% endfor %}
      <td class="n"><b>{{ "%.0f"|format(backtest.cumulative[key][-1]) }}</b></td>
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>
{% endif %}

{# ---------------- 3. Held-out validation ---------------- #}
<div class="srule"><span class="no">3</span><h2>Held-out validation and routing</h2></div>
<div class="prose"><p>The canonical benchmark holds out EPL 2024-25 gameweeks
30 to 38. No single backend wins every position there. Poisson takes
goalkeepers, the heuristic takes defenders, the GBM takes midfielders and
forwards, and the production ensemble is precisely that routing table applied
per position.</p></div>

{{ m.figure(figs.get("fig_holdout_rmse"), "3",
   "Held-out RMSE per position and backend on EPL 2024-25 gameweeks 30-38,
    lower is better. The routed annotation marks the backend the ensemble uses
    for each position.") }}

{# ---------------- 4. Walk-forward ---------------- #}
<div class="srule"><span class="no">4</span><h2>Walk-forward validation on World Cup rounds</h2></div>
<div class="prose"><p>The EPL benchmark cannot answer whether a change survives
the shift to international football. The walk-forward design can. For each
completed round, the GBM trains strictly on earlier data and predicts that
round, so form features and WC retraining are tested leak-free. Config E,
which adds real team xG for/against trailing form from the community WC-2026
dataset, wins the pooled RMSE and is the deployed v4xg model; config D shows
why the proxy-minutes features were rejected, and config F shows that even
REAL lineup minutes pass only marginally and lose to the xG features.</p></div>

{{ m.figure(figs.get("fig_walkforward"), "4",
   "Pooled leak-free RMSE per configuration across held-out WC rounds.
    A is the old form-blind EPL-only model, B adds the form feature, C
    additionally retrains on completed WC rounds, D adds the rejected
    proxy-minutes features, E (deployed as v4xg) adds real xG form from the
    community WC-2026 dataset, F adds real lineup minutes.") }}

{% if walkforward %}
<p class="note">Artifact generated {{ walkforward.generated_at_utc }},
holdout rounds {{ walkforward.holdout_rounds|join(", ") }}.
Regenerate with <span class="num">python scripts/wc_forward_validation.py</span>.</p>
{% else %}
<p class="note">Walk-forward artifact not yet generated. Run
<span class="num">python scripts/wc_forward_validation.py</span>.</p>
{% endif %}

{# ---------------- 5. Calibration ---------------- #}
<div class="srule"><span class="no">5</span><h2>Calibration of pre-match predictions</h2></div>
<div class="prose"><p>For every completed round, the last prediction made while
the fixture was still scheduled is compared with the points the player then
scored. Labels come only from realized data and predictions only from before
kickoff, so this is the honest live record of the production pipeline.
Coverage per backend reflects what actually ran on a given day, mostly the
GBM before July and the ensemble after; thin cells are labeled with their n
rather than smoothed over.</p></div>

{{ m.figure(figs.get("fig_calibration"), "5",
   "Pre-match predicted points against realized points per position, all
    completed rounds, with the identity line dashed and binned means in
    vermillion. Under-prediction of high scores is expected; single-match
    fantasy points are heavy-tailed.") }}

{% if calibration_summary %}
<div class="tbl-wrap">
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Backend</th><th>Pos</th><th class="n">n</th>
    <th class="n">RMSE</th><th class="n">MAE</th><th class="n">Spearman rho</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for r in calibration_summary %}
    <tr>
      <td class="role">{{ r.model_backend }}</td>
      <td class="role">{{ r.position }}</td>
      <td class="n">{{ r.n }}</td>
      <td class="n">{{ "%.3f"|format(r.rmse) }}</td>
      <td class="n">{{ "%.3f"|format(r.mae) }}</td>
      <td class="n">{{ "%.3f"|format(r.spearman_rho) if r.spearman_rho is not none else "-" }}</td>
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>
{% endif %}

{# ---------------- 6. GK formula evolution ---------------- #}
<div class="srule"><span class="no">6</span><h2>The goalkeeper formula, theory against measurement</h2></div>
<div class="prose"><p>The save bonus began as a flat constant, was re-derived
from first principles at 1.13 per unit of opponent xG, and shipped at the
empirically calibrated 0.50 after the sweep showed the theoretical value
overestimates. Not all opponent xG becomes shots on target, and the median
keeper does not save at the elite rate. The episode set the project rule that
derivations propose and measurements decide.</p></div>

{{ m.figure(figs.get("fig_gk_sweep"), "6",
   "Goalkeeper RMSE under the v1 flat bonus and the v2 opponent-xG-scaled
    bonus, on held-out EPL and on realized WC rounds. Deltas annotate the v2
    bars; negative is improvement.") }}

{# ---------------- 7. Match forecasting ---------------- #}
<div class="srule"><span class="no">7</span><h2>Match forecasting and the market-skill audit</h2></div>
<div class="prose"><p>For the closing matches a dedicated forecaster ensembles
four components: a penalized Dixon-Coles model, an xG-weighted scoring-rates
model, leak-free as-of-kickoff country Elo, and the prediction market's
trophy-price ratio. Every component is scored under the same nested
walk-forward protocol used for the fantasy models, and the ensemble weights
are learned from that out-of-sample skill, never hand-set. The audit's
headline: the market proxy LOSES to plain Elo on knockout advance log-loss
{%- if match_forecast and match_forecast.skill_advance %}
({{ "%.3f"|format(match_forecast.skill_advance.market.log_loss) }} vs
{{ "%.3f"|format(match_forecast.skill_advance.elo.log_loss) }})
{%- endif %}, and its learned ensemble weight is capped at
{%- if match_forecast and match_forecast.weights %}
{{ " %.2f"|format(match_forecast.weights.pool_advance.cap) }}
{%- else %} 0.25{% endif %}. Sentiment is a signal, not an anchor.</p></div>

{{ m.figure(figs.get("fig_forecast_skill"), "7",
   "Out-of-sample skill per forecaster component: 90-minute outcome ranked
    probability score on held-out rounds 2-7 (left, dotted line = uniform
    baseline) and knockout advance log-loss on rounds 4-7 (right). Elo wins
    both; the market underperforms Elo despite pricing the same matches.") }}

{% if match_forecast and match_forecast.skill_1x2 %}
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>1X2 RPS</th><th>Advance log-loss</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for key, label in [("elo", "Elo"), ("dixon_coles", "Dixon-Coles"),
                        ("xg_poisson", "xG-Poisson"), ("market", "Market")] %}
    {% if key in match_forecast.skill_1x2 or key in match_forecast.skill_advance %}
    <tr><td>{{ label }}</td>
        <td>{{ "%.3f"|format(match_forecast.skill_1x2[key].rps) if key in match_forecast.skill_1x2 else "-" }}</td>
        <td>{{ "%.3f"|format(match_forecast.skill_advance[key].log_loss) if key in match_forecast.skill_advance else "-" }}</td></tr>
    {% endif %}
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
<p class="note">Artifacts data/evaluation/match_prediction_skill.json and
match_predictions_round8.json; regenerate with
<span class="num">python scripts/match_predictions.py --fit</span>.</p>
{% endif %}

{# ---------------- 8. Negative results ---------------- #}
<div class="srule"><span class="no">8</span><h2>Negative results</h2></div>
<div class="prose"><p>Rejected ideas are results. Each row below was built,
measured under the same gates as everything that shipped, and turned down on
the numbers. Recording them keeps the same mistake from being made twice and
keeps the shipped stack honest about why it looks the way it does.</p></div>

<div class="tbl-wrap">
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Idea</th><th>Tested</th><th>What the measurement said</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for nr in negative_results %}
    <tr>
      <td class="wraps"><b>{{ nr.label }}</b><br><span class="note">{{ nr.summary }}</span></td>
      <td class="num">{{ nr.tested }}</td>
      <td class="wraps">{{ nr.measured }}</td>
      <td class="wraps">{% for e in nr.evidence %}<a href="../{{ e }}">{{ e.split("/")[-1] }}</a>{{ " " }}{% endfor %}</td>
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>

{{ m.figure(figs.get("fig_market_negative"), "7",
   "Change in RMSE when a Benter-style combiner blends Polymarket winner
    prices into each backend, per round. Positive means the market made the
    prediction worse; it did so for every backend in every round tested.") }}

{# ---------------- 8. Reproducibility ---------------- #}
<div class="srule"><span class="no">9</span><h2>Reproducibility</h2></div>
<div class="prose"><p>Every figure and table on this page regenerates from the
repository. The companion notebook,
<a href="../notebooks/model_evolution.ipynb">notebooks/model_evolution.ipynb</a>,
walks the same analyses interactively using the same code paths.</p></div>

<pre class="formula-text">python -m fifa_fantasy.training.validate      # held-out EPL RMSE report
python scripts/wc_forward_validation.py       # leak-free walk-forward artifact
python scripts/model_backtest.py              # cross-model realized backtest
python scripts/gk_formula_ab.py               # GK formula v1 vs v2 A/B
python scripts/with_vs_without_market.py      # market combiner negative result
python -m fifa_fantasy.report                 # this page's dataset and figures
python -m fifa_fantasy.web                    # write the static pages</pre>

{% endblock %}
